==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Lop
<hw>Lop</hw> <pr>(l⟦ocr⟧p)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Lopped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Lopping</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Prov. G.
<ets>luppen</ets>, <ets>lubben</ets>, to cut, geld, or OD.
<ets>luppen</ets>, D. <ets>lubben</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cut
off as the top or extreme part of anything; to shorten by cutting off
the extremities; to cut off, or remove, as superfluous parts; <as>as, to
<ex>lop</ex> a tree or its branches</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧With branches
<xex>lopped</xex>, in wood or mountain felled.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Expunge the whole, or <qex>lop</qex> the excrescent parts.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cut partly off and bend down; <as>as, to
<ex>lop</ex> bushes in a hedge</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lop</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Lop
<hw>Lop</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>That which is lopped from anything, as
branches from a tree.</def> <rj><au>Shak. Mortimer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lop</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Lop
<hw>Lop</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To hang downward; to be pendent; to
lean to one side.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lop</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Lop
<hw>Lop</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To let hang down; <as>as, to
<ex>lop</ex> the head</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lop</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Lop
<hw>Lop</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Hanging down; <as>as, <ex>lop</ex>
ears</as>; -- used also in compound adjectives; <as>as,
<ex>lop</ex>eared; <ex>lop</ex>sided.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lope</ent>⟦br⟧
